## 5. Lighting Concept

- Lighting circuits are derived from configured room light-point counts.
- Day spaces should coordinate ambient, task, accent, fireplace, stair, terrace, and exterior lighting scenes.
- Bedrooms and gallery areas should coordinate switching at entries and bedside/usage positions.
- Final luminaire types, emergency lighting needs, dimming, controls, IP ratings, and code requirements are TBD.

## 6. Socket and Appliance Concept

- Socket planning is derived from configured room socket counts.
- Dedicated appliance circuits are expected for kitchen, laundry, technical room, HVAC, exterior equipment, and high-load optional systems.
- Final outlet spacing, dedicated loads, load diversity, voltage drop, and protection are excluded.

## 7. Kitchen Electrical Concept

- Kitchen configured socket count is included in the room circuit table.
- Appliance loads may include cooking, oven, refrigerator, dishwasher, extractor/range hood, small appliances, and under-cabinet/task lighting.
- Final appliance list, circuit separation, isolators, cable routes, and protection must be designed by a licensed electrician.

## 8. Bathroom Electrical Concept

- Bathrooms and wet rooms require zone, IP-rating, bonding, RCD/RCBO, ventilation, towel warmer, mirror/light, and appliance review.
- This package does not define final bathroom zones or certify safe installation.
- Wet-area rows in the circuit table are placeholders and require licensed review.

## 9. Technical Room Electrical Concept

- Technical room is the assumed location for distribution, controls, heat pump support equipment, water systems, smart-home rack/network gear, PV/battery interfaces where applicable, and monitoring.
- Clearances, ventilation, fire separation, cable containment, labeling, and maintenance access are TBD.

## 10. Terrace Electrical Concept

- Terrace zones require weather-exposed lighting, weather-protected outlets, possible BBQ/outdoor kitchen support, jacuzzi-ready placeholder, and low-level/stair/guard lighting coordination.
- Exterior equipment must be selected and installed for exposure, water ingress, mechanical protection, frost, UV, and safe isolation.
- Jacuzzi-ready does not mean approved for a spa installation.

## 11. Exterior Lighting

- Exterior lighting should address entry, access path, terrace, steps, storage bench zone, facade accent lighting, and dark-sky/glare control.
- Final fixture locations, IP ratings, controls, switching, emergency needs, and cable routes are TBD.

## 12. Grounding and Bonding Placeholder

- Earthing arrangement, main equipotential bonding, supplementary bonding, lightning/interface risks, PV/battery/generator bonding, and terrace/exterior metallic elements require licensed design.
- No grounding or bonding compliance claim is made.

## 13. Surge Protection Concept

- Surge protection should be reviewed due to mountain exposure, possible overhead/long utility runs, PV integration, smart-home electronics, and sensitive equipment.
- SPD type, location, coordination, earthing, and maintenance requirements are TBD.

